<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="531" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,1368,1896]" pageId="30" pageNumber="531">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1728,1752]" pageId="30" pageNumber="531">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[622,789,1728,1752]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Balclutha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="531" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rubrinervis">
<emphasis box="[622,789,1728,1752]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="531">B. rubrinervis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in color, external characters and shape, but can be distinguished from the latter by the dorsal apodeme of the aedeagus being strongly expanded and extended, and distinctly bifurcated apically.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="531" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,1368,1896]" pageId="30" pageNumber="531">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1836,1860]" pageId="30" pageNumber="531">Etymology.</emphasis>
The word “ 
<taxonomicName box="[472,570,1836,1860]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Balclutha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="531" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tricornis">tricornis</taxonomicName>
” refers to the aedeagus with the basal apodeme strongly expanded dorsally and bifurcated on apex, hence the name 
<taxonomicName box="[602,730,1873,1896]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Balclutha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="531" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tricornis">
<emphasis box="[602,730,1873,1896]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="531">B. tricornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
